<seg id=1> Two Captured South Korean Soldiers Fled North Korea, After 45 Years Imprisonment </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Seoul, Reuters) The South Korea National Security Bureau said the day before yesterday that two South Korean soldiers, listed as dead in the Korean War, recently fled North Korea after being imprisoned for at least 45 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> South Korea National Security Plot Bureau stated that 67-year-old Kim Fuki and 71-year-old Park Dong Il had recently returned to South Korea through the third country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> It was stated that the two were captured by Chinese soldiers in the southeast area near the border between South and North Korea during the Korean War. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> It was stated that the two were forced to serve as slaves in North Korea before fleeing. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> South Korea National Defense Ministry listed tens of thousands of missing soldiers as dead after the end of the Korean War in 1950-1953. Kim Fuki and Park Dong Il are two of those names. </seg>
<seg id=7> What South and North Koreas finally signed was armistice agreements but not a formal peace treaty; </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> South and North Koreas technically remain in a state of war. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It was unexpected that these two men became relatives by marriage during their internment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> It was stated that the second son of Kim Fuki and the fourth daughter of Park Dong Il married in April 1991. </seg>
<seg id=11> No more detailed explanation was given in the statement. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> One officer of South Korea National Security Bureau said that Kim Fuki and Park Dong Il were currently being detained by the authorities to gather more details. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> National Defense Ministry had expressed that about twenty thousand soldiers disappeared during the Korea War and National Defense Ministry think more soldiers may yet survive. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> This April a prisoner of war who fled and returned home said that he knew fifty to sixty soldiers from South Korea are currently imprisoned in North Korea. </seg>
</p>
